body:
Consider the following circuit:

``` firrtl
FIRRTL version 6.0.0
circuit Foo: %[[
  {
    "class": "firrtl.transforms.DontTouchAnnotation",
    "target": "~|Foo>b"
  }
]]
  domain ClockDomain:

  layer A, bind:
    layer B, bind:

  public module Foo:
    input a: UInt<1>

    layerblock A:
      layerblock B:
        node b = a
```

When compiled to Verilog (`firtool Foo.fir`), we get:

``` verilog
// Generated by CIRCT firtool-1.138.0-44-g4910cec93
module Foo_A_B();
  wire b = Foo.a;
endmodule

module Foo_A();
endmodule

module Foo(
  input a
);

endmodule


// ----- 8< ----- FILE "layers-Foo-A.sv" ----- 8< -----

// Generated by CIRCT firtool-1.138.0-44-g4910cec93
`ifndef layers_Foo_A
  `define layers_Foo_A
  bind Foo Foo_A a_0 ();
`endif // not def layers_Foo_A

// ----- 8< ----- FILE "layers-Foo-A-B.sv" ----- 8< -----

// Generated by CIRCT firtool-1.138.0-44-g4910cec93
`ifndef layers_Foo_A_B
  `define layers_Foo_A_B
  `include "layers-Foo-A.sv"
  bind Foo Foo_A_B a_b ();
`endif // not def layers_Foo_A_B
```

However, the module `Foo_A()` is empty and doesn't need to exist. (The `layers-Foo-A.sv` must exist per the FIRRTL ABI, though!)

Change `LowerLayers` to recognize when this is happening and not emit this module.

h/t @dtzSiFive for the idea.
